This paper is primarily focused on computer vision tasks related to action recognition and localization, which suggests that it is likely to belong to the cs.CV (Computer Vision and Pattern Recognition) sub-category. The use of convolutional neural networks (ConvNets) and other deep learning techniques also suggests that it may be relevant to the cs.LG (Machine Learning) sub-category. Additionally, the paper discusses the use of temporal information and the preservation of temporal resolution, which could make it relevant to the cs.MM (Multimedia) sub-category. The use of end-to-end training and the exploration of different network architectures could also make it relevant to the cs.AI (Artificial Intelligence) sub-category. Finally, the paper discusses the use of public datasets and the evaluation of experimental results, which could make it relevant to the cs.IR (Information Retrieval) sub-category.
